What the Post Shows
The post features a high-quality 2D quantum simulation of a wavepacket interacting with a smooth potential barrier. 
It visualizes:
The probability density |ψ(x,y,t)|² as the height of the surface.
The phase of the wavefunction (arg ψ) shown through color.
Clear physical effects: reflection, transmission, interference ripples, and quantum tunneling through the barrier.
The video is generated directly from the time-dependent Schrödinger equation.
Simple Explanation
This is a classic demonstration of quantum scattering. A quantum wavepacket (a localized “blob” of probability) travels toward a potential “hill” (the barrier). 
Instead of behaving like a classical particle that either bounces off or goes over the barrier, the quantum wave does both at once:
Part of it reflects.
Part of it transmits through the barrier (even when it classically shouldn’t have enough energy) — this is quantum tunneling.
Interference patterns appear where the reflected and transmitted parts overlap.
The color showing the phase is particularly nice because the phase is what carries the wave-like and interference behavior.
